Data Visualization¶

  • There are a large number of Python data visualization libraries. Overviews can be found at https://pyviz.org.
Name Year PyPI DLs Dec. 2021 Static Images or Interactive Web Characteristics
Matplotlib 2003 25 M Static Images Low level commands. Based on MATLAB. Versatile. Basis for other programs.
Pandas 2008 70 M Static Images Primarily for data handling with dataframes. Very basic plots.
Seaborn 2012 8 M Static Images Based on Pandas and Matplotlib. Must use Matplotlib to change Seaborn defaults.
Bokeh 2012 2 M Interactive Web Based on Grammar of Graphics. Lower level than Plotly and Altair. Supported by Anaconda, but open source.
Plotly 2013 8 M Interactive Web Good for 3D graphs. Based on plotly.js. Has high level commands and optional low level commands. Both open and closed source.
Holoviews 2015 0.2 M Interactive Web Based on Bokeh and Matplotlib. Higher level than Bokeh.
Altair 2016 4 M Interactive Web Based on Vega. Unique data structure. Performs slower when over 5,000 records.
Plotnine 2017 0.2 M Static Images Based on Grammar of Graphics. Python implementation of ggplot. Replaces the no-longer-maintained ggplot Python library.

Matplotlib¶

  • Matplotlib--low level code for static image data visualization created in 2003
  • Many other data visualization libraries, like Seaborn, are built on top of Matplotlib
  • Matplotlib uses the NumPy array for input data
  • The components of a Matplotlib plot are:

  • Figure--instance of class plt.Figure. Like a single container that contains all the objects representing axes, graphics, text, and labels. Object commonly assigned name fig.
  • Axes--instance of class plt.Axes. What we see inside a bounding box with ticks and labels. Object commonly assigned name ax.

  • Matplotlib provides two distinct interfaces:
    1. MATLAB-style--tools within pyplot module. Said to be stateful. It keeps track of current figure and axes, upon which all pyplot commands are applied. Most convenient for very simple plots.
    2. OOP-style--create figure and axes objects. Methods are applied to these objects. Most convenient for more complex plots.

Code Use
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt Module used for many plotting tasks. Conventionally imported as plt.
plt.show() After building plot, used to display plot. When used in script, displays plot in interactive window. Should only be used once per Python script (at the end). If run multiple times, can lead to bugs. When used in Jupyter notebook displays plot inline and can be run in multiple cells. If show() is not used, plots will still display, but will print an ugly piece of text like <seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x1ba6ae1c190> above each plot.
%matplotlib inline Magic command placed near top of Jupyter notebook. Sets up notebook to display Matplotlib plots embedded as static PNG images below code. %matplotlib inline is now the default setting for Jupyter notebooks and is not needed anymore.
plt.figure() Create figure object
plt.axes() Create axes object

EXAMPLES

Seaborn¶

  • Seaborn--high level code for static image data visualization built on top of Matplotlib
  • Matplotlib is a powerful and flexible library. However it requires a lot of low level boiler plate code. We'll use Seaborn where possible and only use Matplotlib as needed.
  • "While you can be productive using only seaborn functions, full customization of your graphics will require some knowledge of matplotlib’s concepts and API. One aspect of the learning curve for new users of seaborn will be knowing when dropping down to the matplotlib layer is necessary to achieve a particular customization"

Data Input¶

  • Seaborn accepts multiple data types such as NumPy arrays, Pandas data frames, and Python lists and dictionaries. Seaborn accepts tidy, "longform" data where each column is a variable and each row is a record. This is similar to R's ggplot2. Seaborn also accepts, "wideform" data stored in two-way tables, but the function calls would use different arguments. Using tidy data is recommended.

Code Use
import seaborn as sns Conventionally imported as sns
sns.load_dataset("<DATASET>") Return specified pandas data frame. Seaborn contains about a dozen data sets that can be used for examples.

Levels¶

  • Seaborn plots can be created using two different "levels". There are subtle differences:
  1. Axes Level--functions apply to Matplotlib axes object
    • Legend placed inside plot
    • Slightly shorter because of legend placement
    • Can be composed with other plots
    • "The axes-level functions call matplotlib.pyplot.gca() internally, which hooks into the matplotlib state-machine interface so that they draw their plots on the “currently-active” axes. But they additionally accept an ax= argument, which integrates with the object-oriented interface and lets you specify exactly where each plot should go:"

  1. Figure Level--functions apply to Matplotlib figure object
    • Legend placed outside plot
    • Slightly taller because of legend placement
    • Can create plots with multiple subplots. This is called faceting.
    • "The figure-level functions wrap their axes-level counterparts and pass the kind-specific keyword arguments (such as the bin size for a histogram) down to the underlying function. That means they are no less flexible, but there is a downside: the kind-specific parameters don’t appear in the function signature or docstrings"

  • "On balance, the figure-level functions add some additional complexity that can make things more confusing for beginners, but their distinct features give them additional power. The tutorial documentation mostly uses the figure-level functions, because they produce slightly cleaner plots, and we generally recommend their use for most applications. The one situation where they are not a good choice is when you need to make a complex, standalone figure that composes multiple different plot kinds. At this point, it’s recommended to set up the figure using matplotlib directly and to fill in the individual components using axes-level functions."

  • Two functions do not fit into the scheme above. These are:

    1. jointplot()--figure level create subplots with JointGrid objects
    2. pairplot()--figure level create subplots with PairGrid objects

Relplot¶

Code Use
sns.relplot() Create scatterplot or line plot, returning FacetGrid object. Arguments include kind="<KIND>", data="<DATA>", x="<NUMERICAL_VARIABLE>", y="<NUMERICAL_VARIABLE>". "scatter" is default kind. For both scatter plots and line plots, hue=, style=, or size= can be set to a variable. Behavior may be different depending on whether variable is numeric or categorical. Multiple of these attributes can be used with the same or different variables. For line plots, by default, observations are grouped by the x variable, group means are calculated, and the line shows the 95% CI. See documentation for more optional arguments.

EXAMPLES

Displot¶

Code Use
sns.displot() Create histogram or KDE plot (density plot), or returning FacetGrid object. Can also create an empirical cumulative distribution function (ECDF) plot which shows the cumulative proportions. Arguments include kind="<KIND>", data="<DATA>", x="<NUMERICAL_VARIABLE>". "hist" is default kind. For histogram, kde=True overlays KDE. For histogram, KDE, and ECDF, hue= can be set to a categorical variable. See documentation for more optional arguments.

EXAMPLES

Histogram

In [15]:
sns.displot(kind="hist", data=penguins, x="body_mass_g", bins=20)
plt.show()

Histogram with KDE

In [16]:
sns.displot(kind="hist", data=penguins, x="body_mass_g", bins=20, kde=True)  # Add KDE to historgram
plt.show()

KDE Plot

In [17]:
sns.displot(kind="kde", data=penguins, x="body_mass_g")
plt.show()

KDE Plot with Hue

In [18]:

plt.show()

ECDF Plot

In [19]:

plt.show()

Catplot¶

Code Use
sns.catplot() Create box plot, bar plot, or violin plot. Arguments include kind="<KIND>", data="<DATA>", y=<NUMERICAL_VARIABLE>. Optionally, use x= and/or hue= to group by categorical variables. For bar plots, by default, they calculate the mean of the numerical variable and display a 95% CI. estimator= and ci= can change this behavior. See documentation for more optional arguments.

Facet¶

Code Use
col="<CATEGORICAL_VARIABLE>" Specify variable whose categories become subplots
col_wrap=# Specify max subplots per row before subplots are wrapped onto the next row
row="<CATEGORICAL_VARIABLE>" Specify variable who categories further divide subplots. Subplots for for a single category are arranged on single row.

EXAMPLES

Facet and Wrap

In [36]:
sns.displot(kind="hist", data=penguins, x="body_mass_g", bins=20, col="species", col_wrap=3)
plt.show()

Facet and Row

In [37]:
sns.displot(kind="hist", data=penguins, x="body_mass_g", bins=20, col="species", row="sex")
plt.show()

Aesthetics¶

  • There are 5 plot themes:
    1. whitegrid--good for comparing numerical values
    2. darkgrid--good for comparing numerical values when dark gridlines interfere with figure
    3. white--good when grid not needed
    4. dark--good when grid not needed
    5. ticks--mix between white and white grid
  • Themes affect many aspects of the plot at once. We can gain finer control of the plot using other functions that despine, change context, modify theme attributes, and change colors.
  • The axes style is similar to the theme, but allows for a lot of customization
  • The context is the spacing and size of plot elements. There are 4 context options:
    1. paper--small elements
    2. notebook--medium small elements. Default.
    3. talk--medium large elements
    4. poster--large elements
  • Spine--the axes number lines/borders
Code Use
sns.set_theme(style="<THEME>") Apply theme to all future plots. If no arguments, uses default theme. Themes include: white, dark, whitegrid, darkgrid, and ticks. See documentation for more optional arguments that control theme.
sns.axes_style() Prints current axes style parameters. Optionally, specify "<THEME>" to print default parameters for that theme.
sns.set_style() Set axes style parameters. Argument is "<THEME>". Optionally, provide a dictionary of key:value pairs similar to those printed by sns.axes_style().
sns.plotting_context() Prints current context parameters. Optionally, specify "<CONTEXT>" to print default parameters for that context.
sns.set_context() Set context parameters. Argument is "<CONTEXT>". Optionally, font_scale=# controls size. Optionally, provide a dictionary of key:value pairs similar to those printed by sns.plotting_context().
sns.despine() Remove, trim, or offset axes spines. Optional argument offset=# bumps the axes back from the data, while trim=True cuts the axes off at the extent of the data.

Colors¶

Code Use
color_palette() Any function that has an optional palette= argument calls this function internally. Can be used to set color of plot elements. The palette may be specified using a string for a prebuilt palette such as "pastel", a list of tuples of RGBA values, or custom palettes. There are many ways to create custom palettes in Seaborn.

EXAMPLES

In [51]:
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
sns.relplot(
    kind="scatter",
    data=penguins, 
    x="flipper_length_mm", 
    y="body_mass_g",
    hue="species",
    palette="pastel"  # Prebuilt palette
)
plt.show()
In [52]:
sns.set_theme(style="whitegrid")
sns.relplot(
    kind="scatter",
    data=penguins, 
    x="flipper_length_mm", 
    y="body_mass_g",
    hue="species",
    palette=[(1, 0, 0, 0.5), (0, 1, 0, 0.5), (0, 0, 1, 0.5)]  # RGBA values with 0 to 1 range
)
plt.show()
